Bookmark                           
                        December 2, 2015 at 1:16PM




 Thank you for reporting this comment. Undo PRO
 

StarCraft Custom Builders Hudson Reed is a trade name of Ultra Finishing, Ltd. of Burnley, Lancashire, UK which was incorporated in 1984 by Stephen Heys to provide electroplating services.
It is now wholly owned by by Ultra Finishing Group, Ltd. and has become largely a merchandiser, having closed its factory in Burnley in 2015.
It sells mostly imported merchandise through Hudson Reed web sites tailored over a dozen countries. Most of the sites are not located in the countries served, but are managed and supported from England. The U.S. site, for example, is wholly virtual. Shipping is handled by a contracted service out of a warehouse in Pennsylvania, and customer support from England. Ultra Finishing has no physical presence in the U.S.
In addition to Hudson Reed, the company owns the following brands: Premier (bath furniture), Niko (bath fixtures and decorative hardware), Balterley (bath furniture), and Old London (traditional English bathtubs). Most of its merchandise is imported from Asia, aided by the acquisition of two Chinese bathroom product manufacturers in 2012, but some of its furniture, some shower pans and a few bath tubs are still made in the U.K..
None of the faucets sold by Hudson Reed are made by Ultra Finishing or made in England. Most of the faucets are from the Whitehaus Collection (made in Israel and Italy) and RGM Distribution, Inc., a Brooklyn, NY distributor that imports its private label Fresca brand faucets from China.. Only a dozen or so of the faucets sold by Hudson Reed are actual Hudson Reed brand faucets. From our research to this point, we know they are made in China, but have not identified the actual manufacturer. We will eventually. It often takes time and a lot of phone calls to suss out the information.
Hudson Reed brand faucets (unlike Fresca and Whitehaus faucets) ...

Are not certified safe and reliable to North American standards (ASME A112.18.1/CSA B125.1) and may not be lawfully installed in North America.
Do not meet the state requirements imposed on faucets by Massachusetts or California and may not be sold, offered for sale or installed in either of those states.
Do not have certifications on file with the Department of Energy as required by the Energy Policy and Conservation Act attesting that the faucets meet the flow restriction of a maximum of 2.2 gallons per minute required of faucets in the U.S.
Have not been tested and certified to meet the requirements of the Energy Policy and Conservation Act and, as a consequence, may not be lawfully sold or offered for sale in the U.S.
Have not been tested and certified to be lead free and suitable for installation in a drinking water system as required by every U.S. and Canadian plumbing code and by the U.S. Safe Drinking Water Act, and may not, therefore, be sold, offered for sale or installed in North America.

For what it's worth.




